## Suggested First 5 Sprints

### Sprint 1 (Truthful Gap Lock)
- Target tasks: `F1-01`..`F1-08`
- Focus: produce the authoritative Java-close syntax/token gap inventory and complete the lexer/token baseline required for the rest of F1
- Exit checks:
  - `F1-G1` green at baseline level
  - no major syntax family needed later in F1 is missing a tokenization plan

### Sprint 2 (Core Syntax Families)
- Target tasks: `F1-09`..`F1-27`
- Focus: land the missing declaration/statement/expression syntax families and lock their parser behavior
- Exit checks:
  - `F1-G2` green at baseline level
  - selected F1 syntax subset parses coherently across realistic source files

### Sprint 3 (Type System + Runtime Enablement)
- Target tasks: `F1-28`..`F1-38`
- Focus: make the newly added syntax semantically real and executable in native builds
- Exit checks:
  - `F1-G3` and `F1-G4` green at baseline level
  - new syntax is not parser-only; representative fixtures build and run

### Sprint 4 (`com.pulse.lang` + Collections + IO Depth)
- Target tasks: `F1-39`..`F1-64`, `F1-83`..`F1-95`
- Focus: expand the stdlib from skeletal to materially useful Java-close baseline, including explicit utility/threading/atomics/concurrency/network/reflection/ecosystem policy instead of leaving those areas implied
- Exit checks:
  - `F1-G5` and `F1-G6` green at baseline level
  - realistic programs can rely on the shipped stdlib rather than only intrinsics/minimal helpers

### Sprint 5 (Integration + Validation Depth)
- Target tasks: `F1-65`..`F1-82`
- Focus: integration, large fixtures, docs, closure evidence, and validation/release guardrails for the locked language/stdlib support boundaries
- Exit checks:
  - `F1-G7`..`F1-G9` green
  - F1 closes with a documented, tested Java-close language+stdlib baseline rather than an aspirational roadmap

## Exit Criteria

| Milestone | Exit Criteria |
|---|---|
| F1 | Tasks `F1-00`..`F1-105` and gates `F1-G1`..`F1-G9` are all `Done (Locked)` |
| F1 Deliverable | PulseCode ships a documented, conformance-tested Java-close language and stdlib baseline where the selected F1 syntax surface is operational end-to-end, benchmarked, and usable in real applications |
